Hey, thanks for offering to contribute 👍  I still think that this approach is still probably the simplest way to go about it.

Most everything that you need should be in [config.py](https://github.com/michael-lazar/rtv/blob/master/rtv/config.py). You will need to add a parser argument for the new ``--refresh-token`` parameter. Probably you will want to remove the ``Config(..., token_file=TOKEN, ...)`` argument from the constructor, and instead have it loaded from the user's configuration settings. One way to go about it might be to switch ``config.refresh_token`` to a property, something like:

```
class Config(object):
    ...

    @propery
    def refresh_token(self):
        return self.config.get('refresh_token', TOKEN)
```

Also, check out [tests/test_config.py](https://github.com/michael-lazar/rtv/blob/master/tests/test_config.py) to make sure that your new paramater is fully tested. It should be pretty straightforward.

Since PEP 557 has been accepted (https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0557) I have given up. If Guido thinks that it is fine to drop the parenthesis in a decorator factory, then it is fine. Starting from today (release 4.2.0) the following code is valid and does what you want:

```python
@decorator.decorator
def printer(func, text='hello', *args, **kwargs):
    print(text)
    return func(*args, **kwargs)

@printer
def world():
    print("World")
```

So the button issue.

currently if the group has any format content other than `{output}` eg `format = "moo {output}"` then that responds to click events but the `{output}` does not capture them.

I think this behaviour makes sense as the {output} is another module and so it should do it's clicks.  Now if that does not respond to the clicks then maybe it makes sense to pass them to the group.  But if I have 
```
group {
   module_no_clicks {}
   module_catches_clicks {}
}
```
then it would be inconsistent when we are using it.

Anyhow I have added a patch that allows uncaught events to be caught and passed to the container (group) that allows the old behaviour (but sticks on a module that captures events).  Maybe we should do some 'clever' stuff at setup eg if all contained modules have no click events and no button then pass on the events.  So anyway I think we are back in a position when all is possible via simple changes we just need to nail down the behaviour we are expecting in the different situations.

This needs to make sense to actual users.

